article.headline: Johnson's career-high 35 lift Miracle
article.linkText: Miracle finally top Rockers after 3 OTs
article.story:
ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- As the night dragged on and the overtimes
stacked up, Pee Wee played like a giant.

	   Shannon Johnson, who is 5-foot-7, scored 15 of her team-record
35 points after regulation and the Orlando Miracle beat the
Cleveland Rockers 103-99 in triple-overtime Saturday night.

	   "I didn't start off very good, but my teammates stayed with me
the whole night,'' said Johnson, whose 11 points in the final
overtime topped her output in the first half by two. "That shows a
lot for my team, because they saw someone struggling and they just
tried to help out.''

	   Johnson played a franchise-best 51 minutes, going 11-for-17 from
the field and 11-for-12 from the free-throw line. She hit a
game-tying shot in the first overtime but was silent in the second
before taking over in the third.

	   "I honestly think she's the best point guard in the league,''
Orlando coach Dee Brown said. "I put it in her hands. I told her,
she has to put the ball in her hands in certain situations and take
advantage of it.''

	   Orlando, which set a franchise record for points, hit 28 of 32
free throws in the game. Johnson made four free throws over the
final 15 seconds, as the Miracle made all eight of their foul shots
in the extra periods of the WNBA's longest game of the season.

	   "We could've easily lost that game twice, but we had enough
heart and character as a team to keep fighting,'' Brown said.

	   Jessie Hicks added a career-high 18 points for the Miracle,
including all six of their points in the second overtime.

	   Penny Taylor scored 27 points to lead Cleveland, 22 after
halftime. Chasity Melvin added 23, 11 in the first half when the
Rockers built a 14-point lead in the opening minutes.

	   It was the first triple-overtime game for both franchises.

	   "For the fans that were here, they got something special and
that was a very great battle between two very good teams,'' said
Taylor, who had 12 points in the overtimes. "In the end, they
prevailed, but I think no one should really be too disappointed
with that game.''

	   Each team missed a chance to win at the end of the first two
overtimes.

	   Merlakia Jones missed a 17-foot jumper from the right wing at
the end of the first overtime and nobody could come up with the
ball for a follow. Jones finished with 17 points and eight
rebounds.

	   And as the second overtime buzzer sounded, Johnson's 14-foot
jumper from the right wing rimmed out.

	   Cleveland briefly held a four-point lead in the first overtime
as Taylor hit a 3-pointer and two free throws.

	   But Adrienne Johnson's 3-pointer cut the deficit to a point, and
Shannon Johnson's layup off an untouched drive through the lane
tied the game at 80 with 17 seconds left in the period.

	   ''(Shannon Johnson) creates so much offense with her ability to
penetrate,'' Cleveland coach Dan Hughes said. "We had a hard time
containing her.''

	   Orlando trailed 71-68 with 20 seconds remaining in regulation,
sent the game into overtime on Katie Douglas' layup at the
11-second mark. But Douglas came up empty on the potential
game-winning free throw, the Miracle's last miss from the line.

	   The Rockers' smothering defense gave them a big lead early.
Forcing six turnovers in as many minutes, Cleveland reeled off 16
straight points for a 20-6 lead. Melvin had eight points, all from
point-blank range, as the Rockers made nine of their first 11
shots.

	   But Orlando slowly crept back. Hicks scored on three consecutive
possessions to cut the deficit to five points, and the Miracle
trailed 32-30 at halftime.
